div.p: During Governor Brian Kempâ€™s press conference this afternoon, he announced that he would extend the Shelter in Place Executive Order through April 30 and said that all provisions will remain in effect.Â ACCG will share that Executive Order as soon as it becomes available.Â He also announced new Executive Orders related to the National Guard, nursing homes and short-term rentals.Â Links to the Governorâ€™s remarks and the Executive Orders released today are below:

span.a: Remarks from Governor Brian Kempâ€™s Press Conference â€“ April 8 at 4:00 p.m.
Executive Order:Â Renewal of Public Health State of Emergency
Executive Order:Â Extending National Guard Support and Adding 1,000 More Troops
Executive Order:Â Ensuring Safety of Employees and Residents of Nursing Homes and Long-Term Care Facilities
Executive Order:Â Suspension of Short-Term Rentals
Flags on State Buildings & Grounds to Fly at Half-Staff to Honor Senator Jack Hill on Friday, April 10

p.span: Governor Kemp Appoints County Advisory Committee for COVID-19 Issues

div.p: On April 7, 2020, Governor Brian Kemp appointed a committee of 15 county commissioners and three county administrators to provide him with recommendations of actions to address issues and concerns stemming from the COVID-19 pandemic as they relate to county governments.Â ACCG President Billy Pittard chairs the committee, which held its first meeting today. Weekly meetings will be held, with key recommendations being conveyed each week to Governor Kemp. ACCG is convening and facilitating meetings of the committee.Â Â Click here to see the County Advisory Committee members.

p.span: ASL Resources Available to Counties for Press Conferences and Public Service Announcements through GEMA

div.p: The Georgia Emergency Management Agency (GEMA) reminds counties that ASL interpreters are available to assist with press conferences, public service announcements, videos and any other public communication regarding COVID-19 for those who are hearing impaired in your community.Â Requests for assistance can be shared through your County EMA Director through WEB EOC.Â If you have any questions or concerns, please contact ACCG Communications Director Schuyler Harding atÂ sharding@accg.org.

span.a: FEMA Reference Document for Messaging and Resource Links

span.span: Just released from the Governorâ€™s office:

div.p: Governor Brian P. Kemp, Lieutenant Governor Geoff Duncan, and House Speaker David Ralston have announced plans to extend Georgiaâ€™s public health state of emergency through May 13, 2020 to mitigate the spread of COVID-19. Under state law, the Governor may renew the public health state of emergency, which was otherwise set to expire on April 13, 2020. Lt. Governor Duncan and Speaker Ralston agree it is necessary for the public health emergency to be renewed and will not be requesting a special legislative session, which was tentatively scheduled for April 15, 2020.Â Â Read the press release here.

IMPORTANT NOTICE: Â Â Below you will find the Governorâ€™s Executive Order regarding the shelter in place declaration and additional information provided by the Governorâ€™s office. Â ACCG is working on a summary that will be provided as soon as possible.

span.span: Governor Kempâ€™s Executive Order Signed April 2, 2020

li.p:
Catoosa County Government is assisting residents who have been impacted by the Easter severe storms by waiving the fees for permits needed to repair and rebuild damaged properties.Â Fees for building, demolition and electrical reconnection permits are being waived for properties that have been listed by inspectors as structurally damaged by the storms.
Residents whose properties are not listed as structurally damaged may contact the Building Inspection Department at (706) 965-4226 for an evaluation of their properties.Additionally, Catoosa County

residents are encouraged to contact the Building Inspection Department before they begin repairs to verify that the contractor they have chosen is properly vetted to work in Catoosa County. â€œBefore beginning work on roofs, buildings or tree removal, please call us to verify that the contractor is properly licensed, bonded and insured to work in Catoosa County,â€ said James Davis, Director of Planning and Inspections. Davis said contractors who have been approved to work in Catoosa County have been issued blue permits that must be displayed on the dashboards of their vehicles, and that residents should avoid hiring workers who do not have the proper blue permits.
To view or report a power outage with NGEMC. Click the following linkÂ https://www.ngemc.com/outage/current

3/20/2020Â As schools across the region close, we have been truly inspired by community efforts to keep neighbors and families nourished. We commend our school systems for quickly developing logistics of food pick-up and deliveries for all children. Several business owners across the region have inspired us with their generosity as they open the doors of their restaurants so that students of their community may eat at no cost.Â Â

div.p:

span.span: The COVID-19 Information page is updated several times a day.Â

BeginningÂ Monday, March 23, 2020, The Catoosa County Administration Building will be closed to the public until further notice. There is a intercomÂ located by the door if you need to speak to someone. Citizens are encouraged to utilize online services provided and/or phone to conduct any businessÂ (706)965-2500Â Â www.catoosa.comÂ

div.p: The Catoosa County Board of Commissioners welcomes you to Catoosa County, "The Gateway to Georgia."Â Our mountain home is a stone's throw away from Chattanooga, and a short, scenic drive to Atlanta.Â Catoosa County enjoys the highest per capital income, and the lowest unemployment rate in the three state Chattanooga metropolitan area.

span.span: Our schools are excellent, and our taxes are currently the 16th lowest among Georgia's 159 counties.
Whether you are a resident, or a visitor, we invite you to enjoy all of the advantages Catoosa County has to offer.Â
